International Information Programs Europe-Eurasia | The Balkans 17 September 2001 Iceland Expresses Sympathy, Solidarity with U.S.
After Attacks
Oddsson letter to Bush; statement by government The fight against terrorism calls for "strong international solidarity," Iceland's Prime Minister David Oddsson said in a message of condolence to President Bush.
Following is the text of his message and a statement by the government of Iceland: (begin text) TO THE PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES FROM THE PRIME MINISTER OF ICELAND Dear Mr. President, The people of Iceland condemn the horrific action against the American nation with the terrorist attacks in New York City and Washington D.C., and convey their deepest condolences.
The fight against terrorism and those who harbour terrorists or help them in any other way calls for strong international solidarity.
The Government of Iceland will not waver in its commitment to that effort.
The Government expresses its solidarity with the Government of the United States of America in its determination that those responsible for the evil which was perpetrated against the American people yesterday are found and punished.
Sincerely yours, [Signed] David Oddsson STATEMENT BY THE GOVERNMENT OF ICELAND The Government of Iceland expresses its profound sorrow at the terrible acts of terrorism which have been perpetrated today against the people of the United States of America.
People in Iceland have felt horror and compassion in witnessing these appalling attacks which have cost numerous innocent citizens their lives.
The Government of Iceland condemns this cowardly act and conveys its deepest condolences to the Government and the people of the United States of America.
Reykjavik, September 11 2001 (end text) __________________________________________________________________
